# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2014-australian-football-international-cup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2002-australian-football-international-cup] The **2002 Australian Football International Cup** was the inaugural international Australian rules football tournament held in Melbourne, Australia in 2002.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2002-australian-football-international-cup] 11 nations participated from around the world and the tournament was officiated by the International Australian Football Council.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2002-australian-football-international-cup] Ireland won the tournament, finishing undefeated and victorious over Papua New Guinea in the Grand Final on 23 August at the Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG).
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2002-australian-football-international-cup] A 22 player All-International squad was named, however names were unplaced and not allocated to any specific field position.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The **2005 Australian Football International Cup** was the second time that the Australian Football International Cup tournament, an international Australian rules football competition was held.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The event was hosted by both Melbourne and Wangaratta, Australia, in 2005.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] 10 nations participated following the late withdrawal of both Nauru and Denmark and the introduction of Spain.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] All sides were scheduled to play 4 games, after which the top 4 sides played off in semi-finals for a berth in the Grand Final decider.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The Grand Final was between Papua New Guinea and New Zealand.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] Both sides went through the tournament undefeated.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] It was played as a curtain raiser to an official Australian Football League premiership season match and was replayed on Fox Sports (Australia) and the Fox Footy Channel.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] New Zealand were crowned international champions for the first time.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The grand final was replayed on Fox Sports (Australia) and the Fox Footy Channel.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The best and fairest medal was awarded to New Zealand's James Bowden.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] Like the All-Australian Team in the Australian Football League, a team selected from the best players in the International Cup was selected.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2005-australian-football-international-cup] Team members were unplaced and not allocated to any specific field position.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The **2008 Australian Football International Cup** was the third time the Australian Football International Cup, an international Australian rules football competition, has been contested.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] It was scheduled for 2008 (as part of the 150th year celebrations of Australian Football), with 16 nations competing.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The tournament was hosted by both Melbourne and Warrnambool in Victoria, Australia between 27 August and 6 September, with a single match additionally played in Geelong.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Like previous tournaments, the competition was open to men's teams with strict nationality eligibility rules.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The Grand Final was played between New Zealand and Papua New Guinea.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Papua New Guinea were victorious by 8 points with a goal kicked after the siren.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Like the Grand Final in previous years, the match was played at the Melbourne Cricket Ground as a curtain raiser to the 2008 AFL Second qualifying Final which attracted a crowd of 76,703 spectators.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] However unlike previous tournaments, the final was not televised.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The AFL later indicated that a regional round and semi-finals would be held in Warrnambool.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The AFL indicated that unlike earlier cups, it would likely be split into two divisions, a premier division and development division, with some discussion as to whether the eligibility rules could be loosened for the development division, to enable more countries to participate.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Leagues were given the opportunity to nominate which they would prefer, with eight in each division being an initial target.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Ultimately, this idea was dropped, with the sixteen teams being seeded into four pools.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] In December 2007, it was announced that Melbourne and Warrnambool would co-host the two division event, with Melbourne matches to be played mainly in Royal Park North.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Several potential new sides were announced by the AFL, including an Israeli-Palestine combination supported by the Peres Centre for Peace, China and India.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The USA Women's team announced an intention to send a squad to play against Australia and possibly Papua New Guinea.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Additionally Canada and England announced their intentions to send Under 17s squads.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] As a result, there was speculation over an inaugural women's and under 17 divisions.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] However the AFL denied these divisions in favour of a senior men's competition only.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] In response, and with the Barassi International Australian Football Youth Tournament being cancelled, British and Canadian junior teams had to organise their own tours and matches against Australian schools.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Despite both international teams being in Australia at the same time, they did not play against each other.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The US women's team announced a 2009 tour instead.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The AFL confirmed in July 2008 that sixteen nations will compete.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] In addition, there will be friendly matches played between Melbourne-based migrant community teams under the names "Team Africa" and "Team Asia", as well as the Tongan side which was unable to commit to the full tournament.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Also despite a previous appearance, the Spain Bulls will not be competing.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The world team was selected based on player performance in the pool rounds only.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2008-australian-football-international-cup] India, China, the Peace Team and Finland all missed representation in the team.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] The **2011 Australian Football International Cup** (also known as the **AFL International Cup 2011** or **IC11**) was the fourth edition of the Australian Football International Cup, an international Australian rules football competition run by the Australian Football League (AFL).
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] It was contested between 12 and 27 August 2011 by 18 nations, with games played in both Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] Two matches were played as curtain raisers to AFL premiership matches, USA vs South Africa at Stadium Australia and the IC Grand Final at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] Ireland won its second men's championship, and the inaugural women's championship (Ryan Aslett Cup).
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] 17 of these clubs represented single nations, and one (the Peres Team for Peace) represented both Israel and the Palestinian Territories.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] The first round of matches was played with modified rules, most significantly the reduction of game length to two-quarters, in the same manner as the 2011 NAB Cup.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] At the conclusion of Round 1, the best two teams from each Group were regrouped into four groups of three teams, based on Win-Draw-Loss performance and Percentage in Round 1, all within a larger group known as Division 1.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] These teams would remain in contention for the International Cup title.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] The remaining six were regrouped in the same way, into two subgroups of Division 2.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] These teams would compete for a secondary prize.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] Division 1 teams played one match against each team in their respective groups.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] Division 2 teams played one match against each team in their respective groups, as well as a single "cross-over" match against a team in the opposite group.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] At the conclusion of Round 2, the teams were once again re-seeded based on their performance in the previous round; the teams in Division 1 were seeded in positions 1-12, and the teams in Division 2 in positions 13–18.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] These matches were played at the same time as the final round 2 Division 2 matches; the Division 2 teams did not participate in this round.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] In the opening round of the Women's International Cup, the five teams played each other once, over the course of 10 days.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] At the conclusion of Round 1, Australia, the lowest ranked team in the competition based on points and percentage, was eliminated and finished in 5th place.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2011-australian-football-international-cup] The remaining four clubs will compete in the finals.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The **2014 Australian Football International Cup** (also known as the AFL International Cup 2014 or **IC14**) was the fifth edition of the Australian Football International Cup, an international Australian rules football competition run by the Australian Football League.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] It was contested between Saturday August 9 to Saturday August 23, with games played in Melbourne.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] All three previous champions (Ireland, New Zealand and Papua New Guinea) participated in the tournament.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] There are 18 nations competing in the 2014 Tournament.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] Of these, 15 competed in the previous tournament; Indonesia and Pakistan make their debuts, while Finland return having previously competed in 2008.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The teams were seeded into three pools of six to decide which teams would play each other, though all teams will be ranked on a single ladder.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The top four teams at the end of Day 3 progress to the International Cup Semi-finals.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The other teams will play another match, depending on their ladder position, with those results added to the Ladder to decide Day 5 matchups.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The 5th to 12th-placed teams will play in Division 1 for the remainder of the tournament, and the 13th-placed team onwards will play in Division 2.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] For the second consecutive time, there was a concurrent Women's tournament alongside the Men's competition.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] Seven teams participated from five countries - the United States and Canada both fielded two teams.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] Each team played four matches across five matchdays.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] Matches played on Saturday 16 August - the "Community Round" of the tournament - were played as curtain-raisers to other amateur Metropolitan and Country football matches to be confirmed; all other games in the round-robin were held at Royal Park, Melbourne.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] After the round-robin tournament, the last placed team was eliminated.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2014-australian-football-international-cup] The other six teams played one extra match to decide the final placings, with the top two teams on the ladder playing in the Women's International Cup Grand Final.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The **2017 Australian Football International Cup** (also known as the AFL International Cup 2017 or IC17) was the sixth edition of the Australian Football International Cup, a triennial international Australian rules football competition run by the Australian Football League (AFL).
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] It was contested between 5–19 August 2017, with games played in Melbourne.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] All three previous men's tournament champions (Ireland, New Zealand and Papua New Guinea) participated in the tournament.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Previous women's winners (Ireland and Canada) also competed in the tournament.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Papua New Guinea achieved its 3rd men's title and Ireland achieved its 2nd women's title.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The 2017 AFL International Cup was played in Melbourne from 5 to 19 August, with 18 men's teams and eight women's teams competing.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The European Crusaders was a combined team made up of women from Britain, Croatia, France, Germany, Ireland, Italy, Poland and Sweden.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] In the table below, the numbers in parentheses refer to the team's Unofficial World Rankings by *World Footy News* prior to the competition.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] For the first time, the men's fixture was played across two divisions.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Division One played four matches against other teams within the division and were ranked from one to ten, with finals to follow between the top two placed teams on the ladder, the third and fourth placed teams, and so on.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The men's Division Two competition and the women's competition saw teams split into two pools of four with each team playing matches against the three opponents in their pool before competing in semi-finals and grand finals based on finishing positions within the pool.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The women's grand final was played at Etihad Stadium as a curtain-raiser to the Round 22 clash between Carlton and Hawthorn.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The men's grand final was played at the Melbourne Cricket Ground as a curtain-raiser to the Round 22 match between Collingwood and Geelong.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The majority of the matches were played at Royal Park in the Melbourne suburb of Parkville.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] The inclusion of a "Community Round" allowed matches to be played as curtain-raisers to local suburban, amateur and country matches.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Additionally, the International Cup introduced a "School Round" to be played on 9 August, with games played at suburban and country schools.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/2017-australian-football-international-cup] Fixtures for the tournament were released by the AFL on 18 July 2017.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/49th-parallel-cup] The **49th Parallel Cup** (formerly PanAm Cup) is an annual representative Australian rules football match between the United States and Canada first contested in 1999.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/49th-parallel-cup] Since 2007 the women's teams have also contested the cup.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/49th-parallel-cup] The men's matches are contested between the United States men's team ("The Revolution") and Canada's men's team ("The Northwind") while the women's matches are contested between the United States women's team ("The Freedom") and Canada's women's team ("The Northern Lights").
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/49th-parallel-cup] The cup is historically paused during the Australian Football International Cup year to enable the countries to compete at that tournament.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/49th-parallel-cup] Between 2015 and 2021 the cup went into recess for several reasons, primarily due to the 2017 Australian Football International Cup followed by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] As the primary news division of the ABC, it is responsible for all news-gathering and coverage across the public broadcaster's various television, radio, and online platforms.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] ABC News has an extensive online presence which includes written news reports and videos, an ABC News mobile app (ABC Listen), podcasts, and in addition, all of the ABC News television programs available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment, and news in other languages.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] Simon Robinson was appointed director of the division on 28 May 2026.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] ABC News, from its inception in 1932, with ABC radio sourced its news from multiple sources, including cable news from London, its own bureaus in Europe, the Middle East and the Asia-Pacific, and in a fashion similar to commercial radio stations from local newspapers around Australia.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] Censorship was rife during the war, particularly after the U.S. entered the conflict on 7 December 1941.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] After General Douglas MacArthur set up his headquarters in Australia, he wielded enormous power, including on matters of censorship.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] Inter alia, he declared that every Australian radio station would only broadcast three news bulletins per day and that these would be simultaneous on all stations (ABC and commercial) at 7.45 a.m., midday, and 7.00 p.m.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] Weather forecasts were banned because it was felt that these may assist the enemy.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] The 7:45 a.m. bulletin was the only one that did not commence on the hour or the half-hour.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] It was placed at this timeslot as initially the ABC sourced its news from newspapers in a deal which required that news would not be broadcast earlier, to ensure newspapers sales were not affected.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] This bulletin continued at this time on ABC Local Radio stations until 19 September 2020, before being cancelled to save costs.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] Notices were issued banning radio stations from broadcasting some major wartime events, but as the federal government did not have the same power over the printed press as it did over the radio, newspapers usually reported events that radio was not permitted to mention.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] The ABC launched its first independent news bulletin on 1 June 1947 after years of negotiations with the Australian Government.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] The *Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983* mandates that the ABC "shall develop and maintain an independent service for the broadcasting of news and information" both within Australia on a daily basis, and also to countries outside Australia.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] The name of the division and director responsible has changed over the years.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] In 2004 it was the News and Current Affairs Division when John Cameron took over as Director from Max Uechtritz as Director.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] The financial year 2008–2009 saw a lot of changes, both in the way that television content was produced as well as an "expansion of international news programming and continuous news across platforms, new programs and a range of appointments to senior positions".
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] Kate Torney became director of the News Division in April 2009.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] In November 2014, a cut of A$254 million to funding over the following five years meant that the ABC would have to shed about 10% of its total staff, around 400 people.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] There were several programming changes, with regional and local programming losing out to national programs, and the Adelaide TV production studio had to close apart from the news and current affairs section.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] In late 2015 Gaven Morris was appointed Director of the News Division.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] On 10 April 2017, ABC News introduced a new visual identity; as part of the changes, ABC News 24 and ABC NewsRadio were both rebranded as simply "ABC News", while their previously-separate social media presences were merged and unified under ABC News accounts.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] The Director's role changed its name to Director, News, Analysis & Investigations in 2017–2018, and as of June 2021 Morris was still in the role.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] During the 2017 to 2018 financial year, the ABC launched "Regional Connecting Communities" program, which provided funding for increased jobs in the regions, as well as more resources for local news, weather and live reporting.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] Justin Stevens was appointed director of the division of ABC News, Analysis and Investigations on 31 March 2022.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] Media executive and producer Kimberly Lynton "Kim" Williams AM was appointed chair of ABC News on 7 March 2024, with the term expected to conclude on 6 March 2029.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] In March 2026, staff at ABC began a one-day strike over pay and working conditions.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] This was the first walk out in 20 years.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] The division is responsible for all news-gathering and production of news output for ABC television, the ABC network of radio stations, and for its online services.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] In 2018 it was estimated that online ABC news and current affairs reached about 4.8 million users in Australia each month.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment and news in other languages.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] The news theme used from the first days of ABC television from November 1956 to 1985 was "Majestic Fanfare", composed by Charles Williams.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] From 1956 until the early 1980s the version used was the abridged version performed by the Queen's Hall Light Orchestra, from a recording made in 1943.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] Each bulletin opened with a clip from the top story of the day, with the title "ABC News" superimposed over the footage.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] Later, this on-screen approach was replaced by a generic graphic title sequence.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] In 1982, to celebrate the ABC's 50th anniversary, a new version of the theme was commissioned, which incorporated both orchestral and new electronic elements.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] With the exception of a period in the mid-1980s, during which a synthesised theme ("Best Endeavours", written by Alan Hawkshaw, which was the theme for Channel 4 News in the UK) was used for around a year, this was used on radio until August 1988, and on television until early 1985.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] A reworking of "Majestic Fanfare" (essentially the original orchestration up one tone) was arranged by Richard Mills and recorded in 1988 by the Sydney Symphony Orchestra.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] From 1985, a theme composed by Tony Ansell and Peter Wall was used for 20 years, even after the 1998 brand refresh.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] In 2010, it was sampled and remixed by the group Pendulum and this revised work went on to be placed #11 on the Triple J Hottest 100 chart on Australia Day 2011.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] The theme for ABC News changed on Australia Day (26 January) 2005, to a piece written by Martin Armiger and John Gray, and for a couple of years it bore a resemblance to the original Peter Wall / Tony Ansell work in the opening signature notes.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] Wall challenged the ABC and was successful in reaching an agreement.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] The opening notes were removed and the work was re-arranged in 2010.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] The theme music from the 2005–2010 era was remixed by Armiger, giving it a more upbeat, synthesised feel.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] In August 2024, the Ansell–Wall theme was revived in an updated form as part of a larger rebranding of ABC News.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] The theme was remastered by David McDonald from the original multi-track studio recording, including a rerecorded piccolo, and layered samples of a children's drumkit (which McDonald had originally bought for his daughter) to add a bassier sound.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] On 4 March 1985, the ABC refreshed its structure and look, when the 7 o'clock news and the following current affairs program (at that time, *Nationwide*) were combined to form *The National*, and moved to 6:30 pm until 8 December 1985.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] After *The National* was deemed unsuccessful, On 9 December 1985, the news was refreshed again with a new set, graphics, and theme.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] In 1998, the set was updated, a new opener featuring a light blue globe and the ABC logo was introduced, and the theme remained the same but was tweaked.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] The graphics also changed to match the new look.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] On Australia Day (26 January) 2005, a new look (along with theme music) was introduced.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] The new look made use of an orange and blue globe motif.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] At the same time the set and graphics received a major overhaul to fit in with this look.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] This package was used until 21 July 2010, a day before the launch of ABC News.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] In January 2010, the ABC announced that a dedicated 24-hour digital television news channel, named ABC News 24 would be launched during the year.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] The new channel commenced preliminary broadcasting with a promo loop in early July 2010, with the ABC re-numbering ABC HD channel 20 to logical channel number 24.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] The channel was officially launched as ABC News 24 at 7:30 pm Australian Eastern Standard Time on 22 July 2010, and simulcast its first hour of transmission on ABC1.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] With the launch of ABC News on 22 July 2010, all 7 pm bulletins across Australia had a graphics overhaul to match the look of the new channel.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] The blue/orange globe style opener was replaced with a series of sliding panels, featuring images specific to each state.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] New sets were built in each capital city studio to match the ABC News 24 set and graphics were changed to match.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] The news bulletins such as *News Breakfast*, *ABC News Mornings*, *ABC News at Noon, ABC News Day,* *ABC News Afternoons*, *The World*, *ABC Late News* and *Weekend Breakfast* are aired on ABC News along with its own 30- and 15-minute hourly bulletins.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] National news updates are presented on ABC TV throughout the day, with evening updates at 7 pm presented live in most states by the respective state news presenters.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] Bulletins focus strongly on issues of state relevance, with a greater inclusion of national and international news items than are found in the news bulletins of commercial broadcasters.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] A national financial bulletin is presented on weeknights by Alan Kohler in Melbourne.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] The ABC's Ultimo studios produces the 8:30 pm weeknight update presented by Joe O'Brien.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] News and current affairs programs are also broadcast on ABC Australia, a channel broadcast to the region outside Australia.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] These include *Four Corners*, *7:30* and *Q+A*.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] ABC news television programs are available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] ABC NewsRadio is a radio station dedicated to news and current affairs.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] It features national news bulletins at :00 and :30, with rolling news coverage during the remainder of each hour.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] In off-peak hours, it broadcasts content from partner providers such as the BBC World Service, NPR, and Deutsche Welle.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] Radio Australia, which covers the Asia-Pacific region, broadcasts regular bulletins produced in Melbourne, featuring reports from foreign correspondents in the region.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] State bulletins are produced by the ABC Local Radio station from the capital city of each state and mainland territory.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] They are broadcast to all ABC Local Radio and Radio National stations in each state, and focus strongly on issues of state relevance, but also feature national and international stories.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] National bulletins air when state bulletins are not produced.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] ABC Local Radio stations previously broadcast a flagship 15-minute state bulletin at 7:45 am, which in its final years was the only bulletin still introduced by the 18-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] All other bulletins were introduced by a 9-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] This bulletin began in 1939 and was discontinued on Sunday 20 September 2020.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] ABC News produces several current affairs programs for radio.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] All share a quasi-magazine format, and investigate stories in greater depth compared to news bulletins.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] All ABC radio stations are available via an ABC News mobile app, ABC Listen, from which podcasts are also available.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] In March 2024, ABC News won the 2023 Gold Lizzie for Best Title at the IT Journalism Awards, a shared honour between ABC News Story Lab and ABC Radio.
[src:2014-australian-football-international-cup/abc-news-australia] ABC News also won Best Gaming Coverage and Best News Coverage.
